What is Git?

Git is a Version Control System (VCS) used to track changes in source code.

It helps developers:

Save project history
Work in teams
Track changes
Restore previous versions
Manage multiple features
What is GitHub?

GitHub is a cloud platform where Git repositories are stored online.

It is used for:

Sharing code
Team collaboration
Backup
Deployment
Open-source projects
Important Git Concepts
1. Repository (Repo)

A repository is a storage area for a project.

It contains:

Project files
Git history
Commits
Branches

Two Types:

Local Repository → Stored on your computer
Remote Repository → Stored on GitHub
Basic Git Commands
1. pwd
pwd
Theory

Displays the current working directory path.

Example Output
D:\Projects\GitDemo
2. ls
ls
Theory

Shows files and folders inside the current directory.

Example
Login.java
Employee.java
3. cd
cd folderName
Theory

Used to change directory/folder.

Go Back
cd ..

Moves one folder back.

4. git init
git init
Theory

Initializes Git in the project.

Internally

Creates a hidden .git folder which stores:

commit history
branches
configurations
tracking information
Output
Initialized empty Git repository
5. git status
git status
Theory

Shows:

modified files
untracked files
staged files
current branch
Most Important Command

Used daily to check project state.

6. git add
git add filename

OR

git add .
Theory

Moves files to the staging area.

Staging Area

Temporary area before commit.

Example
git add Login.java
Add All Files
git add .
7. git commit
git commit -m "message"
Theory

Creates a permanent snapshot/version of the project.

Commit Message

Describes changes.

Example
git commit -m "Added login feature"
Internally

Git stores:

file changes
author
timestamp
commit id
8. git remote add origin
git remote add origin https://github.com/user/project.git
Theory

Connects local repository with GitHub repository.

Terms
remote → external repository
origin → default remote name
9. git push
git push
Theory

Uploads local commits to GitHub.

10. git push -u origin main
git push -u origin main
Theory

First-time push command.

Meaning
-u → sets tracking
origin → remote repository
main → branch name

After this:

git push

is enough.

11. git branch
git branch
Theory

Shows all branches.

Output
main
login-feature
12. Rename Branch
git branch -m master main
Theory

Renames branch.

13. git log
git log
Theory

Displays commit history.

Short Version
git log --oneline
Git Workflow
Step-by-Step Company Flow
Phase 1 — Team Leader Creates Project
Step 1 — Create Project Folder
mkdir company-project
cd company-project
Theory

Creates project folder and enters it.

Step 2 — Initialize Git
git init
Theory

Starts Git tracking.

Step 3 — Add Project Files

Example:

Login.java
EmployeeService.java

Check:

git status
Output
Untracked files:
Login.java
EmployeeService.java
Theory

Git sees files but is not tracking them yet.

Step 4 — Add to Staging
git add .
Theory

Prepares files for commit.

Step 5 — Commit
git commit -m "Initial project setup"
Theory

Creates first project version.

Step 6 — Create Main Branch
git branch -M main
Theory

Sets main branch as primary branch.

Step 7 — Connect GitHub
git remote add origin https://github.com/company/project.git
Check
git remote -v
Theory

Links local repo with GitHub.

Step 8 — Push to GitHub
git push -u origin main
Theory

Uploads project to GitHub.

Phase 2 — Developer Downloads Project
Step 9 — Clone Repository
git clone https://github.com/company/project.git
Theory

Downloads complete project from GitHub.

Internally

Git copies:

files
branches
commit history
Step 10 — Open Project
VS Code
code .
Eclipse

Import Existing Project.

Phase 3 — Developer Starts Work
Step 11 — Pull Latest Code
git pull origin main
Theory

Downloads latest updates from GitHub.

Step 12 — Create Feature Branch
git checkout -b login-feature
Theory

Creates and switches to new branch.

Why Branch?

To work independently without affecting main code.

Phase 4 — Developer Coding

Developer modifies files.

Check changes:

git status
Step 13 — Add Changes
git add .
Step 14 — Commit Changes
git commit -m "Login feature added"
Step 15 — Push Feature Branch
git push origin login-feature
Theory

Uploads feature branch to GitHub.

Phase 5 — TL Reviews Branches
git branch -a
Theory

Shows:

local branches
remote branches
Phase 6 — TL Checks Feature

Switch branch:

git checkout login-feature

See commits:

git log --oneline
Phase 7 — Merge Branch

Switch main:

git checkout main

Merge:

git merge login-feature
Theory

Combines feature branch with main branch.

Phase 8 — Confirm Merge
git log --oneline
Theory

Verifies merged commits.

Phase 9 — Delete Branch
git branch -d login-feature
Theory

Deletes completed branch.

